ng 1340","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1340–":"circa 1340–Overleden","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1350–Female":"1350–Overleden","1370–Male":"1370–Overleden","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","about 1370":"circa 1370","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1340":"circa 1340","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Deceased","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1340":"about 1340","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hancock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name   Hann   + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i>, which was commonly added to personal names (see   Cocke  ).","Dutch: from Middle Dutch <i>hanecoc</i> ‘winkle, periwinkle’ (a type of shellfish), probably a metonymic occupational name for someone who gathered and sold shellfish.","History: Thomas Hancock, the uncle of Declaration of Independence signatory John Hancock (1736/7–93), was among the foremost of 18th-century American businessmen. He was a descendant of Nathaniel Hancock, who was known to have been in Cambridge, MA, as early as 1634. Born in Braintree, MA, John Hancock was president of the Second Continental Congress and the first governor of the state of MA."],"variants":[{"name":"Hancox","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Handcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Hancock   with intrusive <i>-d-</i>."]},{"name":"Hann","meanings":["German and Dutch: from a shortened pet form of the personal name <i>Johann</i> (see   John  ).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Hann</i>, commonly a pet form of <i>Henry</i> (Middle English <i>Hanry</i>). <i>Hann</i> could also be a rhyming pet form of Randolph (Middle English <i>Randal</i>, shortened to <i>Ran</i> or <i>Rand</i>). <i>Han</i> was also a pet form of <i>Joh(a)n</i> in Middle Dutch, and it is possible that this usage was brought to England by Flemings after the Norman Conquest, but no evidence has yet been found that it was similarly used in Middle English. See   Henry   and   Randall  , and compare   Hankin  ,   Hancock  , and   Hanks  .","English: variant of   Ann   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mayor John Hancock was born about 1340, in England, United Kingdom as the son of William Hancok and Mrs William Hancock. He had at least 1 son with Mrs John Hancock."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1340":"umbes 1340","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1340–":"noin 1340–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","1310":"1310","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1340":"noin 1340","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistyn